ce:section.ce:para:
The fluorescent materials synthesis and the construction process of UMIR probe were as shown in 
                        Fig. 1. Generally, the UCNPs-SiO2@MIPs and the B-UCNPs@SiO2 were synthesized, respectively (Fig. 1A), and then mixed physically in proportional to obtain the UMIR probe (Fig. 1B). The SiO2 nanospheres (average diameter size was 80 nm) were employed in the work to as the carrier of the upconversion fluorescence nanospheres (G-UCNPs, diameter size was ~ 20 nm). In the synthesis process, the G-UCNPs were uniformly dispersed on the surface of the silica to interfere their aggregation so as to keep well fluorescence properties. For imprinting layer preparation, the PFOS was used as template molecule, APTES as functional monomer, amino-modified G-UCNPs as auxiliary functional monomer and TEOS as cross-linking agent. The imprinting polymerization occurred in the surface of G-UCNPs-SiO2 composites, and the G-UCNPs can be embedded into the imprinting layers during the process to obtain a stable fluorescence. Under 980 nm excitation, the as-prepared G-UCNPs-SiO2@MIPs has a maximum emission at 546 nm with strong green fluorescence. Meanwhile, B-UCNPs@SiO2 shows a maximum emission at 478 nm with strong blue fluorescence. The UMIR probe was obtained by mingling the G-UCNPs-SiO2@MIPs with B-UCNPs@SiO2 in a final concentration of 4.5 µg/mL and 6.0 µg/mL, respectively. The constructed probe has double fluorescence emission peaks at 546 nm and 478 nm under the excitation of 980 nm. During the PFOS detection process, the recognition cavities on the G-UCNPs-SiO
                           2
                        @MIPs surface can specifically bind to PFOS, consequently leading to the quenching of G-UCNPs fluorescence at 546 nm. The fluorescence quenching could be attributed to the photoinduced electron transfer (PET) between the amino groups in G-UCNPs-SiO
                           2
                        @MIPs surface and the sulfonic groups in PFOS. In a certain PFOS concentration range, the fluorescence intensity of G-UCNPs-SiO
                           2
                        @MIPs decreased with the increase concentration of PFOS added, whereas the fluorescence intensity of the B-UCNPs@SiO2 remained stable, so the PFOS was quantitatively determined accordingly.
